---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "What's the difference between lopping and pruning?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "In the trade they mean the same thing — selective branch removal. In practice, the word 'lopping' has become shorthand for the bad version: flat-cutting the top off a tree, also called 'topping'. We use 'lopping' the way the customer searches for it, but what we actually do is AS 4373 pruning — branch-collar cuts that let the tree heal. We never top healthy trees, because topping destroys structure and creates dangerous epicormic regrowth that drops limbs in storms 5–10 years later." } },
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "How much of the canopy can you safely remove?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "AS 4373-2007 sets the limit at 25% of live canopy in a single growth season for a healthy mature tree. Stressed, drought-affected or recently-transplanted trees should have less. Removing more pushes the tree into stress response — it shoots epicormic regrowth from dormant buds, often weakly attached, and the cuts heal slower. We'll tell you if what you're asking for exceeds the safe budget for the tree, and what the staged plan looks like." } },
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "What is deadwooding and do I need it?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Deadwooding is removing dead branches from a tree while leaving the healthy structure intact. You need it when (a) there are dead limbs over driveways, paths or play areas (falling-branch risk), (b) the tree is mature and the dead wood is a beetle / borer / fungal entry point, or (c) you want to reduce summer storm risk. Healthy mature gums shed dead branches naturally — that's how widow-makers form. Deadwooding a 20m gum is $400–$1,200 depending on size and access." } },
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "Why is 'topping' so bad?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Three reasons. First, the cuts don't heal — they're not at the branch collar so the tree can't compartmentalise the wound, and decay enters straight down the trunk. Second, the tree responds with epicormic shoots from dormant buds under the bark — dozens of them, growing fast (1–2m/year), all attached by thin bark unions. Within 5–10 years those shoots are dangerous. Third, you've removed the photosynthetic engine, so the root system retreats and the tree slowly starves. We see topped gums fall every storm season. If a tree is genuinely too big for its position, the answer is removal, not topping." } },
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "Can you prune for clearance from powerlines?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes — within the customer-owned clearance zone (under 1m from your service line). For the energised distribution lines (high-voltage and SWER) we coordinate with AusNet or Powercor; sometimes they'll do the prune as a network-maintenance item, sometimes they require an accredited climber to do it under isolation. We hold the relevant powerline-trained tickets." } },
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "When is the best time to prune a tree?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "For most Cardinia Shire species: late autumn to mid-winter (May–July). Trees are dormant, cuts heal faster in spring growth, no leaves to dispose of. Eucalypts can be pruned year-round but late-spring/early-summer cuts attract more borer activity. Stone-fruit and ornamentals follow species-specific timing. Storm-damage cleanup is whenever it happens — we don't wait for the season. Formative pruning of young trees is best in the first 3–5 years before any branch exceeds 50mm." } },
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "How much does lopping or pruning cost?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Small ornamental crown lift or thinning: $300–$600. Medium tree (8–15m) deadwood and weight-reduction prune: $600–$1,200. Large mature gum or oak (15–25m+) full crown maintenance: $1,200–$2,500. Multi-tree formative pruning of a row of advanced trees: $800–$2,000. Always quoted on-site, fixed-price, written." } }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Tree Lopping & Pruning Pakenham | AS 4373 Cardinia Shire | (03) 9003 0108"
  description="Tree lopping, pruning, crown thinning, deadwooding & weight reduction across Pakenham, Officer, Beaconsfield & Cardinia Shire. AS 4373 compliant cuts. We don't top healthy trees. $300–$1,500."
  canonical="https://cardiniatreeservices.com.au/services/tree-lopping/">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">AS 4373 pruning &middot; crown work &middot; deadwooding</span>
      <h1>Tree lopping &amp; pruning in <span class="accent">Pakenham &amp; Cardinia Shire</span>.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        Crown thinning, deadwooding, weight-reduction prunes, formative pruning,
        powerline clearance. Every cut to AS 4373 &mdash; branch collar, no
        stubs, no flush cuts. We don&rsquo;t &ldquo;top&rdquo; healthy trees,
        because topping destroys structure and creates the dangerous regrowth
        that drops limbs in storms.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Get a fixed-price quote</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>What we actually do (and what we won&rsquo;t).</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <h3>The five pruning operations.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Crown thinning</strong> &mdash; selective removal of small/medium internal branches to reduce wind sail without changing the tree&rsquo;s outline. Helps storm performance and lets light/air through to the understorey. ~$500&ndash;$1,200 for a mature tree.</li>
          <li><strong>Crown lifting</strong> &mdash; removing the lower branches to lift the canopy clear of driveways, paths, signs, sightlines, swimming pools. ~$300&ndash;$800.</li>
          <li><strong>Crown reduction (weight reduction)</strong> &mdash; shortening end branches back to a suitable lateral, reducing length without flat-cutting the top. Used for long-limb gums leaning toward houses. ~$800&ndash;$1,800.</li>
          <li><strong>Deadwooding</strong> &mdash; removing dead, dying, diseased and broken branches. The most important storm-prep prune. ~$400&ndash;$1,200.</li>
          <li><strong>Formative pruning</strong> &mdash; structural pruning of young (under 10-year-old) trees to develop strong scaffolds and prevent codominant stems. The cheapest tree investment you&rsquo;ll ever make. ~$150&ndash;$400 per tree.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">What we won&rsquo;t do.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Top a healthy tree.</strong> Topping = flat-cutting the head off. It destroys the tree. We won&rsquo;t do it. If a tree is too big for its position, the honest answer is removal.</li>
          <li><strong>Stub-cut a branch.</strong> A 6&ndash;12 inch stub left on a trunk dies back and rots. We cut at the branch collar &mdash; clean, healable.</li>
          <li><strong>Flush-cut a branch.</strong> Cutting into the trunk past the branch collar tears the cambium and lets decay straight into the trunk. We don&rsquo;t do it.</li>
          <li><strong>Remove more than 25% of canopy in a season.</strong> The AS 4373 safe-removal limit. More than this stresses the tree and triggers epicormic regrowth.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>Real Cardinia Shire prune jobs we do every week.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <h3>The Pakenham new-build gum on the boundary.</h3>
        <p>
          Pakenham&rsquo;s growth-corridor estates were built into ex-paddock
          eucalypt remnants. The 15&ndash;20m gum on the back fence was there
          before the house, and it&rsquo;s now overhanging the new neighbour&rsquo;s
          colorbond. <strong>Crown reduction on the eastern aspect, deadwooding
          throughout</strong> &mdash; takes the storm risk away without
          destroying the tree. $1,200&ndash;$2,000 typical.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">The Beaconsfield established oak shedding into the pool.</h3>
        <p>
          Older Beaconsfield blocks have planted English oaks now 60&ndash;80
          years old, dropping autumn leaves into pools and gutters. <strong>Crown
          lift + selective dead/diseased removal</strong> &mdash; doesn&rsquo;t
          change the tree shape, lets sun and air through. Done in winter to
          minimise sap loss. $800&ndash;$1,500.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">The Cardinia Lakes block with 6 advanced ornamentals.</h3>
        <p>
          New estate landscapers plant advanced 3m magnolias, pears and gleditsias
          with crossing branches and codominant stems. <strong>One round of
          formative pruning</strong> in the first 3 years saves $5K+ in
          structural prunes a decade later. $400&ndash;$800 for a six-tree set.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">The Officer rural block messmate near powerlines.</h3>
        <p>
          Older Officer acreage with mature messmate or peppermint gums leaning
          into Powercor service lines. <strong>Clearance pruning under
          powerline tickets</strong>, coordinated isolation if needed. Powercor
          will sometimes do this as a network item; if not, we do it under
          isolation. $600&ndash;$1,500.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>Where we work.</h2>
      <div class="areas-grid">
        <a class="area-pill" href="/pakenham/">Pakenham</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/officer/">Officer</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/beaconsfield/">Beaconsfield</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/cardinia-lakes/">Cardinia Lakes</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/heritage-springs/">Heritage Springs</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/cardinia-shire/">All Cardinia Shire</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <div class="cta-block">
        <h2>Get a fixed-price prune quote.</h2>
        <p>Honest assessment. AS 4373 cuts. No topping. Free on-site visit.</p>
        <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content:center;">
          <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
          <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Book online</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
